<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="707" pageId="2" pageNumber="706" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,1078,1727]" box="[160,294,1078,1103]" pageId="2" pageNumber="706">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,294,1078,1103]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="706">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,1078,1727]" lastBlockId="3.[160,1156,142,305]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="707" pageId="2" pageNumber="706">Small size. Body slightly flattened, pubescent. Head hypognathous; frons transverse; antennal tubercles moderately elevated with rounded apex; maxillary palpi slightly longer than labial palpi; last maxillary and labial palpomeres fusiform; mandibles about as long as 3/4 of frons width, moderately curved, triangularly excavated on basal half of outer side; genae distinctly shorter than length of lower eye lobe. Eyes coarsely faceted; area of connection of ocular lobes not strongly narrow, with about four rows of ommatidia; distance between upper eye lobes slightly larger than width of one upper lobe. Antennae 11-segmented, longer than body; scape elongate, sub-fusiform; antennomeres filiform, length gradually smaller towards XI; antennomere III longer than scape. Prothorax distinctly wider than long; sides with large, rounded tubercle. Pronotum with two large, very elevated plate-shaped tubercles on each side of central area; with row of coarse, deep punctures near anterior and posterior margins. Prosternum centrally notably narrower than width of prosternal process. Prosternal process gradually widened towards apex; maximum width about 3/4 of procoxal cavity diameter. Procoxal cavities closed posteriorly. Mesoventral process without tubercle; wide, gradually narrowed towards apex; posterior width about 3/4 of mesocoxal cavity diameter. Scutellum gradually narrowed towards rounded apex. Elytra gradually narrowed from humerus to apex; posterior width smaller than half of humeral width; humeral width about 1.6 times posterior prothoracic width; with large, elevated, longitudinal carina at centre of basal fifth; apex truncate, with outer angle slightly projected; coarsely punctate; with moderately long and sparse, erect dark setae. Femora pedunculate-clavate. Mesotibiae obliquely sulcate dorsally at distal half. Metatarsomere I slightly shorter than II and III together. Abdominal ventrite I longer than II, III and IV, shorter than V; ventrite V longitudinally sulcate centrally on basal half; apex truncate.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="707" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[160,1156,350,825]" box="[160,262,350,375]" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,262,350,375]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[160,1156,350,825]" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">
<taxonomicName authority="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Barclay, 2019" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Barclay" authorityYear="2019" box="[160,292,385,409]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Noxnympha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[160,292,385,409]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Noxnympha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[300,406,385,409]" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melzeri" authorityYear="1931" box="[552,720,385,409]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Cosmotomidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[552,720,385,409]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Cosmotomidius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[736,824,385,409]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1583,1606]" captionTargetBox="[166,1149,142,1551]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[166,1149,142,1551]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 1. (a–d) Noxnympha eris, holotype female: (a) dorsal habitus; (b) ventral habitus; (c) lateral habitus; (d) head, dorsal view. (e–h) Cosmotomidius setosus, male: (e) dorsal habitus; (f) ventral habitus; (g) lateral habitus; (h) head, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675561" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675561/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(e 
<emphasis box="[850,863,385,409]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">–</emphasis>
h)) as follows: body stout; humeral width about 1.6 times posterior prothoracic width; the lateral tubercles of prothorax are distinctly rounded; outer elytral apex slightly projected. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melzeri" authorityYear="1931" box="[160,328,489,513]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Cosmotomidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[160,328,489,513]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Cosmotomidius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the body is slender, humeral width is about 1.4 times posterior prothoracic width (except in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Martins and Galileo" baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[418,541,524,548]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Cosmotomidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="egregius">
<emphasis box="[418,541,524,548]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">C. egregius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), lateral tubercles of prothorax spiniform, and outer elytral apex with long spine. It differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1943" box="[697,786,558,582]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Zikanita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[697,786,558,582]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Zikanita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[808,917,558,582]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="12.[160,225,1469,1492]" captionTargetBox="[164,1152,143,1437]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[163,1153,142,1438]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 3. Zikanita perpulchra: (a) dorsal habitus, female; (b) mesoventral process, lateral view, female; (c) ventral habitus, female; (d) dorsal habitus, male; (e) ventral habitus, male; (f) head, frontal view, female; (g) elytra, lateral view, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3675565" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3675565/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Figures 3</figureCitation>
(a 
<emphasis box="[937,950,558,582]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">–</emphasis>
g), 4(a 
<emphasis box="[1026,1039,558,582]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">–</emphasis>
f)) by the rounded lateral tubercles of prothorax (spiniform in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1943" box="[771,860,593,617]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Zikanita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[771,860,593,617]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Zikanita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), pronotum without dark sub-reniform pubescent maculae (presents in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1943" box="[679,768,628,652]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Zikanita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[679,768,628,652]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Zikanita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and body without very long and white setae (present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1943" box="[422,511,662,686]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Zikanita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[422,511,662,686]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Zikanita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Barclay, 2019" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Barclay" authorityYear="2019" box="[530,662,662,686]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Noxnympha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[530,662,662,686]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Noxnympha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[669,773,662,686]" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
also somewhat resembles species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bates, 1861" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1861" box="[190,424,697,721]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Anoreina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[190,288,697,721]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Anoreina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bates HW" box="[296,424,697,721]" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" pagination="147 - 152" refId="ref7550" refString="Bates HW. 1861. XV. Contributions to an Insect Fauna of the Amazon Valley. Coleoptera: longicornes. Annal Mag of Nat Hist London. 8 (3): 147 - 152. doi: 10.1080 / 00222936108697391" type="journal article" year="1861">Bates, 1861</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Martins and Galileo, 2008" authorityName="Martins and Galileo" authorityYear="2008" box="[437,869,697,721]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pyrianoreina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[437,574,697,721]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Pyrianoreina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Martins UR &amp; Galileo MHM" box="[582,869,697,721]" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" pagination="69 - 73" refId="ref8235" refString="Martins UR, Galileo MHM. 2008. Notas e novos taxons em Acanthoderini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Lamiinae). III. Generos semelhantes a Anoreina. Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia. 48 (10): 69 - 73. doi: 10.1590 / S 0031 - 10492008001000001" type="journal article" year="2008">Martins and Galileo, 2008</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Julio and Monne, 2005" authorityName="Julio and Monne" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Trichoanoreina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[932,1096,697,721]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="707">Trichoanoreina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Julio CEA &amp; Monne MA" pageId="3" pageNumber="707" pagination="446 - 447" refId="ref7858" refString="Julio CEA, Monne MA. 2005. Novo genero de Acanthoderini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Revista Brasileira de Entomologia. 49 (4): 446 - 447. doi: 10.1590 / s 0085 - 56262005000400003" type="journal article" year="2005">Julio and Monné, 2005</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in particular by the presence of strong pronotal tubercles (absent in these genera), and by the basal elytral carina strongly elevated (not or slightly elevated in these genera).
</paragraph>
